const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '₹18,000-32,000', annual: '₹2.2-3.8 lakh' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: '₹26,000-44,000', annual: '₹3.1-5.3 lakh' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: '₹35,000-60,000', annual: '₹4.2-7.2 lakh' },
  { category: 'Indian Private (if available)', monthly: '₹3,000-8,000', annual: '₹36,000-96,000' },
  { category: 'Private Hospital Visit', monthly: 'Pay per visit', annual: '₹1,500-5,000/visit' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in India 2026 | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in India. Medical tourism, Ayurveda, Indian visa options, and coverage for expats 65+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in India"
  subheadline="India offers incredible cultural depth, affordable living, world-class private hospitals, and Ayurvedic wellness—with long-stay visa options for those of Indian origin."
  heroImage="/images/countries/india-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose India</h2>
  <p>
    India offers extraordinary diversity—from Himalayan retreats to tropical beaches, ancient temples to modern metros. For those with Indian heritage, returning for retirement makes cultural sense. Medical tourism is well-established with world-class hospitals at fraction of Western costs.
  </p>

  <p>
    Goa provides beach living with expat community and Portuguese heritage. Kerala offers Ayurvedic wellness and backwaters. Pondicherry has French charm and spiritual retreats. Bangalore and Pune provide modern cities with excellent healthcare. Himalayan hill stations offer cooler climates.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Private hospitals excellent; public varies widely</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> English widely spoken; Hindi + regional languages</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of Living:</strong> ₹50,000-150,000/month (~$600-1,800); very affordable</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Varies dramatically by region; tropical to alpine</li>
      <li><strong>Visa:</strong> OCI for Indian diaspora; long-stay options available</li>
      <li><strong>Medical Tourism:</strong> World-class private hospitals at low cost</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">India's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    India has a vast private healthcare sector that rivals anywhere globally. Apollo, Fortis, Max, and Manipal hospital chains offer world-class care with doctors trained in US, UK, and Europe. Private hospitals attract medical tourists for cardiac surgery, orthopedics, and more at 20-30% of Western costs.
  </p>

  <p>
    Public healthcare (government hospitals) is very limited and not recommended for expats. The gap between private and public is enormous. Quality private care is concentrated in major cities. Smaller towns and rural areas have limited options.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Location Matters Enormously</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800 mb-0">
      India's healthcare quality varies dramatically by location. Major cities (Delhi, Mumbai, Bangalore, Chennai, Hyderabad) have world-class private hospitals. Smaller cities have adequate private clinics. Rural areas have minimal facilities. Choose your location carefully based on healthcare access.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    India offers various pathways depending on your background:
  </p>

  <h3>OCI (Overseas Citizen of India)</h3>
  <p>
    For people of Indian origin (former Indian citizens, descendants). Lifelong multiple-entry visa with no stay restrictions. Can work and live indefinitely. The preferred option for Indian diaspora. Parents/grandparents of Indian citizens eligible.
  </p>

  <h3>Long-Term Visa</h3>
  <p>
    For foreigners with proven ties to India—marriage to Indian citizen, business interests, volunteer work. Can be 5-10 years with multiple entry. Not specifically for retirees but can work.
  </p>

  <h3>Tourist Visa (e-Visa)</h3>
  <p>
    For shorter stays. e-Visa allows 90-180 days per visit. Some nationalities get 5-year multiple entry. Not ideal for full-time residence but allows extended visits.
  </p>

  <h3>No Pure Retirement Visa</h3>
  <p>
    India doesn't have a dedicated retirement visa for foreigners without Indian connection. OCI is the primary pathway for permanent residence.
  </p>

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance requirements for India:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>OCI holders:</strong> No insurance requirement but strongly recommended</li>
    <li><strong>Long-stay visa:</strong> Comprehensive insurance may be required</li>
    <li><strong>Healthcare access:</strong> Private hospitals expect insurance or cash payment</li>
    <li><strong>Age limits:</strong> Indian domestic insurers have strict age restrictions</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Insurance Strategy for India</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800 mb-0">
      International insurance is essential for seniors—Indian domestic insurers rarely cover foreigners over 65, and existing coverage often has low limits. International plans provide access to top private hospitals and evacuation if needed. Private care is affordable enough that many pay cash for routine visits.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
  <p>
    For seniors in India, international insurers are essential as domestic options are limited:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3>Why These Providers Work for India</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Strong Indian network, direct billing at top hospitals</li>
    <li><strong>BUPA Global:</strong> Highest entry age (79), excellent coverage</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good Asia-Pacific network, competitive pricing</li>
    <li><strong>Now Health:</strong> Asia-focused, good Indian coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Get Personalized Senior Quotes</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Compare coverage from international providers that work well in India.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get BUPA Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for India are moderate—but essential given limited domestic options:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Higher deductibles:</strong> ₹2-5 lakh deductible reduces premiums significantly</li>
    <li><strong>India-only coverage:</strong> If not traveling, exclude other regions</li>
    <li><strong>Direct pay routine:</strong> Private consultations ₹1,000-3,000; cash is easy</li>
    <li><strong>Ayurvedic/wellness:</strong> Often not covered; budget separately if desired</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 1: NRI Returning Home, 68</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> Indian-American with OCI. $2,500/month pension. Returning to Pune.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Cigna Global for comprehensive coverage. Direct billing at Ruby Hall, Jehangir Hospital. Covers US visits.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~₹28,000/month (~$340). Excellent coverage at top hospitals plus US visits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 2: British OCI Holder, 72</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> Born in UK, parents from India. OCI holder. Moving to Kerala for Ayurveda.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> BUPA Global for main coverage. Uses Amrita Hospital, Kochi for serious needs. Pays cash for Ayurvedic treatments.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> BUPA ~₹35,000/month (~£350). Ayurveda treatments separate. Excellent quality of life.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 3: Canadian Snowbird, 66</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> 6 months Goa, 6 months Canada. Pension CAD $3,000/month.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Allianz Care worldwide. Covers both India and Canada. Uses Manipal Hospital Goa when needed.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~₹25,000/month (~CAD $380). No need for separate policies; single comprehensive coverage.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can foreigners without Indian heritage retire in India?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Difficult for long-term. India doesn't have a retirement visa for foreigners. Tourist visas allow extended visits (90-180 days). Business or employment visas require work. Marriage to Indian citizen or long-term business ties can enable longer stays. OCI is the main pathway for permanent residence.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How good are Indian private hospitals?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Top private hospitals (Apollo, Fortis, Max, Manipal) are world-class. JCI-accredited, internationally trained doctors, modern equipment. India is a major medical tourism destination. Cardiac surgery, joint replacements, cancer treatment at 20-30% of US/UK prices with comparable outcomes.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about Ayurveda and alternative medicine?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        India is the homeland of Ayurveda with authentic practitioners, particularly in Kerala. Also yoga, naturopathy, and other traditional systems. Most international insurance doesn't cover these—budget separately. Quality varies; seek established centers with certified practitioners.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is India safe for seniors?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Generally yes in middle-class areas and developed cities. Traffic is chaotic; pedestrian safety requires care. Air quality is poor in North Indian cities (Delhi particularly). Goa, Kerala, Pondicherry, hill stations offer cleaner air and relaxed environment. Choose location based on lifestyle needs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Ready to Compare Options?</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Get quotes from providers that work well with India's top private hospitals.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/allianz-care" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Allianz Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-0">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Insurance requirements, visa regulations, and healthcare access rules change regularly. Always verify current requirements with Indian authorities and consult with a licensed insurance professional.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
